
*********
Citations
*********

Software Citation
=================

If you use the latest version of the Structural-Rounding software, you must cite:

	M. Hooper, B. Lavallee, C. Perschon. B.D. Sullivan, and A. van der Poel. (2020).
	Structural-Rounding: Version 2.0. Zenodo.

..code-block::tex

	@misc{Structural-Rounding_v2.0,
		title={Structural-Rounding: Version 2.0},
		author={Matthew Hooper and
				Brian Lavallee and
				Cole Perschon and
				Blair D. Sullivan and
				Andrew van der Poel},
		month={apr},
		year={2020},
		doi={},
		url={}
	}


If using Version 1.0, you must cite the following:

	B. Lavallee, B.D. Sullivan, and A. van der Poel. (2019).
	Structural-Rounding: Version 1.0. Zenodo. 10.5281/zenodo.3401541

..code-block::tex

	@misc{Structural-Rounding_v1.0,
		title={Structural-Rounding: Version 1.0},
		author={Brian Lavallee and
				Blair D. Sullivan and
				Andrew van der Poel},
		month={sep},
		year={2019},
		doi={10.5281/zenodo.3401541},
		url={https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3401541}
	}

If you use any of our published algorithms, you should *also*
cite the relevant paper(s) as directed below.

=============================================================

The methods in sr_apx:vc:lift (which are used in the main pipeline :program: `main.py` and `main.cpp`) implement the structural rounding framework described in:

	E.D. Demaine, T.D. Goodrich, K. Kloster, B. Lavallee, Q.C. Liu, B.D. Sullivan, A.Vakilian, and A. van der Poel.
	Structural Rounding: Approximation Algorithms for Graphs Near an Algorithmically Tractable Class.
	27th Annual European Symposium on Algorithms (ESA 2019).
	http://drops.dagstuhl.de/opus/volltexte/2019/11158


	B. Lavallee, H. Russell, B.D. Sullivan, and A. van der Poel.
	Approximating Vertex Cover using Structural Rounding.
	2020 Proceedings of the Twenty-Second Workshop on Algorithm Engineering and Experiments (ALENEX).
	https://epubs.siam.org/doi/abs/10.1137/1.9781611976007.6

..code-block::tex

	@InProceedings{demaine2019structural,
		title={Structural Rounding: Approximation Algorithms for Graphs Near an Algorithmically Tractable Class},
